Retry - “This might work if I try again later.”
A retry means re-attempting an operation after it fails.


Timeouts - “Don’t wait forever”
A timeout limits how long you’re willing to wait.

Circuit Breaker (Pattern) - “Stop trying when things are clearly broken”
Closed (normal)
    Requests flow normally
    Failures are monitored
Open (failure mode)
    After reaching the % of failure → stop calls immediately
    Fail fast
Half-open (test mode)
    Try a determined number requests
    If success → close again
    If failure → open again

Why is this core important? Imagine several microservices depending on a response from service A, 
we can keep trying to get a response from it, or it could be a deterministic way to know when it should 
expect a response from it. 

A library implementation of this pattern is resilience4j:
    public class ProductService {

        private final CircuitBreaker circuitBreaker;

        public ProductService() {
            // 1. Configure the Circuit Breaker
            CircuitBreakerConfig config = CircuitBreakerConfig.custom()
                .failureRateThreshold(50) // Threshold for opening the circuit (50%)
                .waitDurationInOpenState(Duration.ofSeconds(60)) // Wait time before trying to close (60 seconds)
                .permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState(5) // Calls allowed in half-open state for testing
                .build();

            CircuitBreakerRegistry registry = CircuitBreakerRegistry.of(config);
            this.circuitBreaker = registry.circuitBreaker("productService");
        }

        public String getProductDetails(String productId) {
            // 2. Decorate the function call with Circuit Breaker
            return CircuitBreaker.decorateSupplier(
                circuitBreaker, () -> fetchProductDetailsFromRemoteService(productId)
            ).get();
        }

